arch:property.oc:show_val: The southern wall of the Chapel is composed of ten courses of nicely hewn and diagonally dressed ashlars. In the eastern corner, decorated plaster still adheres to the wall. The preserved height is 4.00 m in the center.
In the southwest of the trench.
Locus 17 west bedrock escarpment and Locus 36 hexagonal pavement in Chapel.

Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The remainder of the subterranean canalization is installed including the East Plaza Great Cistern. The East and South Perimeter Walls are installed and Rooms A and B and the Tabun Cave Room are built into the casemate of the East Perimeter Wall. The East Plaza and South Passageway are paved and the temple Forecourt is raised and laid with a small hexagonal pavement. Residential Quarter is built in the southwest corner of the precinct. Also at this time the Central Staircase of Phase II is blocked and the lateral East and West Staircases are constructed to access the Lower Temenos.
Closing elevation: -4.00 m or 905.587 m at Sub datum H.
Opening elevation: 0.00 m or 909.587 m at Sub datum H.

Construction of walls including the South Perimeter Wall and associated elements and pavement. In this phase, the Anteroom, Shrine Room and other rooms behind the South Perimeter Wall are constructed and furnished.
Locus 19 east wall of Chapel; Locus 25 plaster adhering to Loci 16 and 19; Locus 21 east niche blocks; Locus 22 west niche blocks; and Locus 28 bottom platform of niche.
